## PARA layout

- **triage/** - landing zone for anything that doesn't obviously fit elsewhere; emptied via `/para-triage` at the next review.
- **projects/** - {{what a "project" means here. Default: time-bound work with a committed deliverable and deadline, one folder per project, each holding a `brief.md` + `actions.md` and, where relevant, a `sources/` subfolder.}}
- **areas/** - ongoing responsibilities. `business/` = running narrative and strategic actions. `network/` = one file per person.{{ Add any other area subfolders this vault needs.}}
- **resources/** - reusable reference. `prompts/` = reusable specs and drafts. `ideas/` = concept-stage ventures with no committed outcome; same `brief.md` shape as a project for easy promotion. `scripts/` = persistent tools the vault needs; their runtime state lives *outside* the vault (see "Integration scripts and their state" below).
- **archive/** - inactive artifacts. `meetings/` = dated meeting/chat/email records.{{ Add `projects/` = completed work and `ideas/` = shelved concepts, if this vault archives finished projects and retired ideas (both filled by `/para-archive`).}}

Promote `resources/ideas/<x>` to `projects/` when one of: someone is waiting on a deliverable by a date; money or a formal engagement is committed; a go/no-go review is on the calendar. Ideas with no traction at 6+ months retire to `archive/ideas/` (via `/para-archive`).

Root `README.md` is the master document, single source of truth for identity, operating model, and track record. Derived outputs regenerate from it.

### Archive hygiene

What a clean `archive/` looks like (applied on the way in, and audited by `/para-deep-clean`):

- **No live work in the archive.** An archived entity has zero open actions - every item done, or open items softened to an explicit "fully closed; minor gaps not material" note. Surviving work is routed out *before* archiving (to a successor idea, an existing project, or `areas/business/actions.md`), never left as a dangling `[ ]`. A closed project must not keep surfacing in `/para-daily-brief`.
- **History archives; living references go to `resources/`.** Brief, actions, and one-time migration/handoff notes are history - they archive with the entity. Reusable material (playbooks, positioning/strategy docs, templates, anything other live work links to as a resource) is *not* buried in the archive; route it to `resources/<name>/`.
- **No loose files at the archive root.** Everything under `archive/` lives in a subfolder (`meetings/`, `projects/`, ...). A stray top-level file is misfiled.
- **Minimum record.** Each archived entity carries a status marker (why it's archived) and a `brief.md`/`README.md`, so it's self-explanatory years later.
- **Zero dangling links.** Moving something into the archive repoints every inbound reference (contacts, areas, README, other entities) in the same pass; a stale link is rot. A historical mention *inside* the archived folder itself is fine.

## Filing rules

- **Contacts**: one file per person at `areas/network/<firstname-lastname>.md` (kebab-case, no diacritics). Relationship context at the top, `## Next actions` appended at the bottom.
- **Actions**: co-locate with the project, idea, or contact they belong to. Per-project actions live in `projects/<project>/actions.md`; per-idea actions in `resources/ideas/<idea>/actions.md`; per-contact actions inside the contact file. Strategic work not tied to one of those goes in `areas/business/actions.md`. Never create a monolithic root `actions.md`.
- **Dated meeting/chat/email artifacts**: `archive/meetings/YYYYMMDD Description.ext`.
- **Source documents**: {{the naming convention for filed documents, e.g. `YYYYMMDD <Who> <Description>.<ext>`. The /para-triage skill applies this convention literally; if you leave it undefined, /para-triage will ask before renaming anything.}}
- **Shared workstreams across contacts**: track actions in the primary contact's file; the other files get a pointer line.
- **Project brief + relationship**: the contact file is the relationship summary; the project folder holds the brief and execution detail. Cross-link both ways.

## Authoritative sources

Pick the source of truth *before* answering, not after. The recurring failure is querying the wrong surface first - the wrong mailbox, the newest file instead of the one sitting in `triage/`, a hand-kept table in a brief over the system that actually owns the data - and only catching it on correction. Naming the owning surface up front pre-empts it.

- **Check `triage/` before searching by date.** An item waiting to be filed is usually the current one; a file found by "most recent" may be a stale copy.
- **Prefer machine-readable exports and system-of-record data over hand-maintained tables in briefs.** A table typed into a brief is a convenience copy; the export, the model, or the live connector owns the truth. When they disagree, the system wins and the brief gets corrected.

